# Dev Portal Migration Guide - Zuplo Docs
created: 2026-03-23, last updated: 2026-05-28, [Read more](https://zuplo.com/docs/dev-portal/migration)

### Setup Instructions
1. **Create a New Routes File**: In your Zuplo project, create a new OpenAPI file called `legacy.oas.json` (or any name you prefer).
2. **Add a Route**: Inside this file, add a route that matches the legacy path and redirects to the new Dev Portal domain.
You must set the path to the path used by the previous Dev Portal, such as `/docs(.*)`.
It's important not to
make the route `/docs(.*)` not `/docs/(.*)` in order to also match the root
path `/docs`.
For example:
...
},
...
"pathMode": "url-pattern"
},
"get": {
"summary": "Redirect",
"description": "Redirect to the new Dev Portal domain",
"x-zuplo-route": {
"corsPolicy": "none",
"handler": {
"export": "legacyDevPortalHandler",
"module": "$import(@zuplo/runtime)",
"options": {
"mode": "redirect"
}
},
"policies": {
"inbound": []
}
},
"operationId": "dev-portal-redirect"
}
}

# Zuplo Routing - Zuplo Docs
created: 2026-03-23, last updated: 2026-04-30, [Read more](https://zuplo.com/docs/articles/routing)

Zuplo uses the OpenAPI document to determine how to match incoming requests to
the defined routes.
The matching process is based on the HTTP method and the
path of the request.
Zuplo will look for a matching route in the OpenAPI
document and will use the corresponding request handler to process the request.
...
To customize or change the order of route matching within a single OpenAPI file,
reorder the path entries in the `paths` object.
The first path defined in the
file will be matched first, followed by the second, etc.
For example, if you want `/users/admin` to be matched before `/users/{userId}`,
place it first in your `routes.oas.json`:
```
Code
{
"paths": {
"/users/admin": {
"get": {
"operationId": "get-admin-user"
}
},
"/users/{userId}": {
"get": {
"operationId": "get-user"
}
}
}
}
```
...
When organizing routes, place more specific paths before more general ones to
ensure correct matching.
Wildcard routes and catch-all patterns should typically
be placed last.
